post_text: "This year has been a crazy ride for the performing arts but as the age old saying goes "The Show Must Go On" and so it shall here with RRHS Hawk Theatre Program. This year we bring to you a season titled "The Unexpected Guest" which centers around the idea to always expect the unexpected especially in chaotic times. Our students will be taking these timeless classics and adapting them to meet the needs of today. Everyone in the program will maintain the standards issued to us by the district to ensure the health and safety of every individual. Ticket purchases and streaming information will be posted on our district media and sites as we approach the dates for each show. Be also on the lookout for additional pop up Thespian performances! If you have any questions, want to donate, etc please contact Director Ellison at jellison@scv35.org.‚Äù

post_text:
October 12th - Proposed return for in-person learning

The Arizona Department of Health Services (ADHS) recommends specific COVID19 school benchmarks be met for two weeks in order to provide in person learning.

As of August 27th, 2020, Santa Cruz County has not met the recommended benchmarks and therefore will not be returning to in person classes on Monday August 31st. The new targeted date for in person learning will be October 12th.

We will continue to monitor the benchmarks for Santa Cruz County and adjust the date as needed. We will continue to send out the SCV35 Weekly Video update and benchmarks via email every Friday. We will also communicate any changes via school messenger, social media, on our website.

For more information regarding COVID19 benchmarks for schools visit the Arizona Department of Health Services website.

For more information, please visit our website. https://www.scv35.org/school_info/reopening_plan

Superintendent David Verdugo discusses how SCV35 is preparing students.

"The market is changing drastically, and Santa Cruz County already had high unemployment rates. We‚Äôre trying to help our students prepare for new opportunities within local industries.

For example, at our agriculture farm, students can learn to become inspectors. We‚Äôre incorporating engineering, technology, and logistics to teach students about the autonomous driving industry. We‚Äôre starting to teach welding because there is a need at the new zinc mine."

The Arizona Department of Administration (ADOA) and the Arizona Department of Health Services (ADHS) have partnered with Hanes to provide free face masks to Arizonans that need them the most.

We encourage parents on behalf of students, school staff members, or anyone who may not be able to purchase a mask to place an order on the ADHS website.

Each order will provide 5 washable, reusable cloth face masks. One order is allowed per household.

https://www.azdhs.gov/preparedness/epidemiology-disease-control/infectious-disease-epidemiology/index.php#novel-coronavirus-order-masks
text:
The Arizona Department of Administration (ADOA) and the Arizona Department of Health Services (ADHS) have partnered with Hanes to provide free face masks to Arizonans that need them the most.

During this time of social distancing we invite you to join our friends at First Things First for a free virtual screening of the documentary No Small Matter on May 19th, from 12:00-1:00 pm.

Nearly 75% of Arizona's licensed child care programs have closed since March and we do not know how many will shut down permanently. As we reopen our economy child care is a top concern for employees and employers.Learn about what happens inside a quality early learning center and what it has to do with workforce development.
We hope to "see" you there!

The purpose of the SCV35 Distinguished Hall of Fame is threefold:
First, to recognize and honor individuals who have made outstanding contributions to SCV35 as well as those categories listed above.
Second, to establish in the hearts of our youth, a motivating influence to excel and to encourage the adoption of lofty goals in the pursuit of excellence.
Third, to foster pride, preserve scholarship, creativity, artistic and academic excellence and citizenship by contributing to the welfare of our school and community.Individuals and performing groups are eligible for selection if they have met any of the following criteria.

After thoughtful consideration, the RRAC has decided to cancel our Track & Field Summer Day Camp, originally planned for June 22nd - 26th.

Even though it is still about 2 months away, there is still a lot of uncertainty around how long the statewide stay-at-home order will remain in effect or how quickly facilities will be able to safely open up.

During this down time, we hope the families in the communities we serve are finding meaningful ways to stay connected and as active as possible.

Remember to maintain a safe social distance, and be sure to let your enthusiasm and positivity shine through!

Santa Cruz County, Arizona
April 1 at 3:00 PM ¬∑

Santa Cruz County is in the TOP 10 of counties that have responded so far! Come on Santa Cruz County, let's make it to #1.

It has never been easier to respond to the 2020 Census on your own, whether online, by phone, or by mail - all without having to meet a census taker. Remember, April 1, 2020 is Census Day. We encourage all Arizonans to self-respond as soon as possible and make Arizona the state with the highest 2020 Census self-response rate in the nation!

Go to 2020census.gov or call 1-844-330-2020 and cross it off your TO DO list today.

Good evening families,

As you may be aware, Governor Ducey and Superintendent of Public Instruction Kathy Hoffman announced earlier today that school closures in Arizona will be extended through April 10th.

Our Grab and Go meal program will continue as planned beginning Monday, March 23rd. Also on Monday, teachers will begin to send students work electronically.

For families who do not have internet access, packets will be available at meal pick up sites. Pick up sites are Calabasas School, Coatimundi Middle School and Mountain View Elementary School. We appreciate everyone's efforts during this time.

Please wash your hands and stay healthy! We miss our students but understand that this is what's best for our community.

Dear SCV35 Families,

In response to Governor Ducey and Superintendent Hoffman's announcement regarding the state wide closure of all schools SCV35 will be shutdown through March 27.

The SCV35 Governing Board a long with district administration will meet this week to determine our next steps.

Beginning Tuesday, we will offer meals for students. We will share the specifics of the meal program Monday.

We are grateful for your patience and understanding as we continue to work through this difficult situation. We will continue to update you frequently.
shared_text:
Governor Doug Ducey is with Superintendent Kathy Hoffman and Arizona Department of Education.
March 15 at 11:14 PM ¬∑

We‚Äôre joining together to keep Arizona‚Äôs kids, families, and school communities safe and healthy. Arizona is united, and we‚Äôll get through this. Superintendent Kathy Hoffman

This decision is not made lightly, but it is the right thing to do to bring certainty and consistency to all Arizona schools. With schools closing, we are working together to provide assistance during this time and lessen the impact on all Arizona families.

It‚Äôs important for families & parents to know that while this will address operational issues, closing schools will not stop the spread of #COVID19. It is the recommendation of public health officials that kids who are not at school remain at home to the greatest extent possible.

For more information on ways to stay safe and healthy, visit http://azhealth.gov.

Read our full letter here: https://azgovernor.gov/governor/blog/2020/03/open-letter-arizona-families-educators-school-leaders-and-education-community

This count impacts the federal funds that communities receive for special education, classroom technology, teacher training, after-school programs, school lunch assistance, and more. Help us shape the futures of all of our kids!

post_text:
Introducing Mijo and Mija our livestock protection dogs at the RRHS farm.

Before Mijo and Mija arrived, the farm was experiencing a loss of chickens continuously for two years. Since their arrival we have not lost any animals to predators.

Mijo and Mija recently added 6 new puppies to the farm. The puppies will be used to teach the proper care of companion animals, as nonlethal methods of reducing livestock loss, and for FFA fundraising.

SCV35 recycles! Do you? Make our recycling efforts count!
If you are recycling in Santa Cruz County you need to remember this.....
Plastic bags should never be recycled!

Don't
Bag recyclables
Recycle bags at the recycle station

Do
Reuse/re-purpose your grocery bags
Recycle grocery bags at your grocery grocery store (ask if they have a collection bin)
